<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-418-028  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 418 028.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  April 30 1990 v36 n1807 p42(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Firms debut instrument language. (Standard Commands forProgrammable Instruments)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Winkler, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A consortium of nine US and European 'rack and stack' testequipment manufacturers are developing a programming languagestandard called 'Standard Commands for Programmable Instruments(SCPI).andP;  This is an attempt to resolve the standards debate in theelectrical equipment industry.andP;  The SCPI instrumentation interfacelanguage is a combination of Tektronix Inc's Analog DataInterchange Format and HP's Test andamp; Measurement Systems Languageand an expansion of IEEE's 488.2 guidelines.andP;  SCPI uses high-levellanguage resembling English to define the interfaces amongincompatible testing equipment.andP;  Consortium members expect fulldevelopment of the standard to take another two years but regardits initiation as a welcome and belated first step.andP;  SCPI may helpsmaller manufacturers compete with very large vendors by reducingthe need for frequent and complex reprogramming.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardizationProgramming LanguagesTest EquipmentElectrical Equipment IndustryConsortia.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>